Years of poor oyster harvests have waterman Bill Beck worried about the future of the industry for his son.
Recently, disease-free oysters were available for harvesting, bringing hope to families like the Becks.
Despite dwindling oyster populations in the Chesapeake Bay, efforts are being made to revive the industry.
Concerns about introducing Asian oysters into the bay have sparked debate among experts and officials.
The need for funding and research to support the oyster industry is crucial for its survival.
Watermen and seafood processors are facing challenges due to low harvests and immigration restrictions.
